etymologies: mid 19th century. From Tasmanian Aboriginal (south-eastern) bubiala

definitions: Any of various Australian shrubs or trees which are typically found in sandy or coastal regions; specifically (a) a subspecies of wattle, Acacia longifolia sophorae (family Fabaceae), which has spikes of bright yellow flowers; (b) any of several shrubs or small trees of the genus Myoporum (family Scrophulariaceae), which have clusters of small pink or white flowers and are frequently cultivated as ornamental plants, hedges, and windbreaks; also with distinguishing word.
